      <h2>Safety Instructions</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Never use a damaged, bent, vibrating, or out-of-balance accessory.</strong>
      </div>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Always wear proper eye protection while using this handpiece.</strong> Wear safety glasses or a face shield whenever you operate a Foredom flexible shaft machine or any power tool to prevent serious eye injury.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>Before attaching this handpiece, read these instructions completely. See your power tool owner&rsquo;s manual for complete instructions on use and maintenance.</li>
        <li>Always make sure your power tool is unplugged during any maintenance procedure.</li>
        <li>Be sure the shank size of the accessory matches the collet size. Inserting an accessory that is too small or too large may damage the collet.</li>
        <li>Never screw the chuck nut back on too tightly. Tightening an empty collet or inserting an incorrectly sized accessory shank may damage the collet.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Adjusting the Shaft and Sheath</h2>

      <div class="note">
        This adjustment does not apply to slip joint connections (H.44TSJ).
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-44t/p01_01.png" alt="Diagram showing sheath, shaft, set screw, motor connector, motor coupling, and motor shaft" />
        <figcaption>Flexible shaft assembly &mdash; sheath, shaft, set screw, motor connector, and motor coupling</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>It is important to check the sheath and shaft tip and properly adjust them before attaching this handpiece to your Foredom flex shaft tool. The tip of the flexible shaft should extend 3/4&Prime; beyond the end of the sheath.</p>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-44t/p01_04.png" alt="Shaft tip extending 3/4 inch beyond the sheath, shown against a ruler" />
        <figcaption>The shaft tip should extend 3/4&Prime; beyond the end of the sheath</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Hang the motor and shaft/sheath fully extended, or lay them on a flat surface.</li>
        <li>Loosen the set screw in the motor connector.</li>
        <li>Move the sheath in or out until the shaft tip extends 3/4&Prime; beyond the sheath.</li>
        <li>Tighten the set screw in the motor connector.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Attaching the Handpiece to the Flexible Shaft</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-44t/p01_03.png" alt="Key tip on end of shaft and keyway slot inside back end of handpiece" />
        <figcaption>Keyway connection &mdash; align the key tip on the shaft with the keyway slot in the back of the handpiece</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Look into the back end of the handpiece for the keyway slot.</li>
        <li>Be sure that the key tip of the flexible shaft is properly lined up with the keyway slot in the back end of the handpiece.</li>
        <li>Push the handpiece onto the shaft. If the key tip is not aligned, turn the shaft tip or the handpiece to the correct position.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>To remove the handpiece, simply pull it off the shaft and sheath with a firm grip while the motor is not running.</p>

      <div class="note">
        The H.44TSJ has a &ldquo;slip joint&rdquo; connection for use with European-style machines.
      </div>

      <h2>Changing Accessories</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-44t/p02_01.png" alt="H.44T handpiece with pin inserted in pilot hole, wrench applied to chuck nut, and bur mounted" />
        <figcaption>Inserting the pin and applying the wrench to change an accessory on the H.44T</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Insert the pin provided into the pilot hole and through the spindle hole (turn the spindle to align the holes).</li>
        <li>Apply the wrench and loosen the chuck nut slightly by turning counterclockwise.</li>
        <li>Insert the shank of the accessory into the collet.</li>
        <li>Tighten the chuck nut with the wrench, keeping the pin in the pilot hole.</li>
        <li>Test for a secure hold by pulling on the accessory.</li>
        <li>Remove the pin.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        Be sure the shank size of the accessory is paired with the same size collet. Inserting an accessory that is too small or too large may damage the collet.
      </div>

      <h2>Changing Collets</h2>

      <p>The different-size collets that come with your handpiece are for holding burs and other accessories with different shank sizes.</p>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-44t/p02_05.png" alt="Chuck nut and collet close-up" />
        <figcaption>Chuck nut (left) and collet (right)</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Insert the pin into the pilot hole and through the spindle hole (turn spindle to align holes).</li>
        <li>Apply the wrench and unscrew the chuck nut by turning counterclockwise.</li>
        <li>Remove the chuck nut to expose the collet.</li>
        <li>Pull the collet out of the handpiece shaft. Pliers are useful for removing collets.</li>
        <li>Slip the new collet in place and screw on the chuck nut with the pin and wrench.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/foredom-44t/p02_04.png" alt="Using pliers to remove a collet from the handpiece shaft" />
        <figcaption>Pliers are useful for removing collets from the handpiece shaft</figcaption>
      </div>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Never screw the chuck nut back on too tightly.</strong> If you tighten an empty collet or insert an accessory shank that is too small or too large, you may damage the collet.
      </div>

